    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1251505958" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1251505958" />
    <a title="Cate Brooks" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/238174-cate-brooks"><img alt="Cate Brooks" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1188167748p2/238174.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1251505958?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cate Brooks" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cate Brooks" href="/user/show/238174-cate-brooks">Cate Brooks</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/238174-cate-brooks?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/238174-cate-brooks?shelf=food-for-thought">food-for-thought</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/238174-cate-brooks?shelf=bee-cave-book-club">bee-cave-book-club</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/238174-cate-brooks?shelf=audio">audio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1251505958" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17362853395663722759">I wonder how horrible of a person it makes me to only give 3 stars to a book about an incredibly humanistic idealist doctor of infectious disease in 3rd world countries. My rating more reflects on how much I enjoyed the read. I struggle with NF. I often find it redundant after a while and like other NF reads, I felt inertia build to read through to the end since there was no bigger narrative that made me wonder &quot;how will this turn out?&quot; &quot;What is the resolve of this story&quot;. I&apos;ll own that as my ow</span>
  <span id="freeText17362853395663722759" style="display:none">I wonder how horrible of a person it makes me to only give 3 stars to a book about an incredibly humanistic idealist doctor of infectious disease in 3rd world countries. My rating more reflects on how much I enjoyed the read. I struggle with NF. I often find it redundant after a while and like other NF reads, I felt inertia build to read through to the end since there was no bigger narrative that made me wonder "how will this turn out?" "What is the resolve of this story". I'll own that as my own issue but I will say that I got bogged down after awhile. I did take great interest in bits and details about drug resistant viruses (esp after the recent Ebola outbreak) and enjoyed following the lines of philosophy about how you make decisions for areas in such desperation. Mill's Utilitarianism breaks down pretty quick under those circumstances. <br /><br />The passage that got me the most was the part where he broke down when the mother he tried to treat with Eclampsia died. He was upset with himself about how much he emoted for her case, in particular. Though he felt for other others he had treated, this case hit him harder since his wife had just given birth. He felt selfish for essentially "feeling" more towards someone who shared experiences like his rather than just feeling towards everyone equally since they are all part of the human condition. I was interested in this concept he brought up. The idea that we kind of pick and choose (even subconsciously) what tragedy and ills in the world we feel connected to. Which one will touch us the most? Which one are we the most compassionate towards? Is the the Boston Marathon bombing because we have friends there or once ran that race? What about the boat of immigrants that capsized and left hundreds dead? Can we emote as much for those people as well? Or is that too much further from our experience? <br /><br />Farmer is beyond remarkable. Full stop. <br /><br />Still I had a hard time getting my mind around the work he was doing. It is so big. Trying to take in the scope of empathy and compassion and work required to even make any sort of impact was like trying to open my mouth wide enough to take a bite out of a full sized watermelon. There was no starting point that I could find.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17362853395663722759" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


